Anonymous Wed 09 Dec 2020 23:56:14 No.34645477 Report
Quoted By: >>34646161
>>34645144
Usually I think in terms of a chapter. One chapter can lead to another, but a short story is self-contained enough where you introduce an idea and give the reader some resolution in that sitting.
So you're looking much more at a character driven story than a plot driven one. Doesn't mean you can't cram plot in, but cut everything but that intro stinger and the few paragraphs of resolution.
Novels breathe even when they're fast paced. Short stories sting you with an idea or event.

Guy meets girl against the backdrop of a interstellar civil war that keeps dragging them from each other - bad scale for a short story, too many scenes & worldbuilding.

Guy is a independent merchant pilot. Flights are assigned by lottery. He scores one of the most coveted runs, but his navigator is killed by one of the large factions. If he doesn't undock from the station in 2 hours, he loses the job. He meets rookie female navigator who also needs to get off the station, pronto.
They put their problems together, undock just in time for a 6 month journey, and leave the almost certain murderer (and the reason she needed to get gone) a surprise to be sprung...ohh, 10 minutes later.
